[Luhansk is a city near the eastern border of Ukraine with Russia; Luhansk is the capital and administrative center of Luhansk Oblast, but was captured by the Luhansk People's Republic (LPR), a rebel group that has held the city and the southern half of Luhansk Oblast since 2014 (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luhansk and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luhansk_People%27s_Republic). Rubizhne, where the 2nd case of diphtheria has been reported, is a city in Luhansk Oblast with a population of about 60 000 residents in 2013, over 100 km northwest of the city of Luhansk, outside the territory controlled by the LPR (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rubizhne). A map of Ukraine that shows the location of Luhansk can be found at http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/ukraine.pdf.

In the early 1990's, a diphtheria epidemic emerged in the Newly Independent States (NIS) of the former Soviet Union, which included Ukraine; the diphtheria epidemic was attributed to disruption of vaccine supply and economic difficulties associated with the dissolution of the Soviet Union (http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/eid/vol4no4/vitek.htm). At the time, Ukraine had "among the highest diphtheria incidence in the world" (http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00036675.htm). In 1995 and 1996, as a result of concerted national and international efforts, the NIS raised adult and childhood coverage and began to control the epidemic, although over 2700 cases were still reported in 1998 (http://wwwn.cdc.gov/travel/destinationUkraine.aspx). - Mod.ML

